Feedback is one of the most essential tools for education, helping guide our students to become more effective and educated computer scientists. Two common forms of feedback are knowledge-based (e.g., content knowledge, assignment efficacy) and behavior-based (e.g., submission habits, engagement) feedback. Although previous research has investigated knowledge-based feedback in some detail, behavior-based feedback has received comparatively little attention. We are in the process of investigating student perceptions about the use of a submission-based feedback tool used in a CS2 course. We adapted tangentially relevant frameworks due to a lack of relevant frameworks, but wanted verify their relevance through a mixed methods approach. This poster outlines our two-step process utilizing Nominal Group Technique (NGT), a structured focus group method, to generate questions for a survey instrument used with a larger audience. We found this method to be successful in supporting the adaptations from existing frameworks, and revealing new factors that students find important for inclusion in the quantitative survey.